323	\label{section-geometrically-reduced}
324	
325	\noindent
326	If $X$ is a reduced scheme over a field, then it can happen that $X$
327	becomes nonreduced after extending the ground field. This does not happen
328	for geometrically reduced schemes.
329	
330	\begin{definition}
331	\label{definition-geometrically-reduced}
332	Let $k$ be a field.
333	Let $X$ be a scheme over $k$.
334	\begin{enumerate}
335	\item Let $x \in X$ be a point.
336	We say $X$ is {\it geometrically reduced at $x$}
337	if for any field extension $k'/k$
338	and any point $x' \in X_{k'}$ lying over $x$
339	the local ring $\mathcal{O}_{X_{k'}, x'}$ is reduced.
340	\item We say $X$ is {\it geometrically reduced} over $k$
341	if $X$ is geometrically reduced at every point of $X$.
342	\end{enumerate}
343	\end{definition}
344	
345	\noindent
346	This may seem a little mysterious at first, but it is
347	really the same thing as the notion discussed in the algebra chapter.
348	Here are some basic results explaining the connection.
349	See also Lemma \ref{lemma-geometrically-reduced-dense-smooth-open},
350	which implies that ``geometrically reduced'' is equivalent
351	to ``generically smooth'' for varieties over a field.
