1576	Purely inseparable extensions are the opposite of the separable
1577	extensions defined in the previous section. These extensions only
1578	show up in positive characteristic.
1579	
1580	\begin{definition}
1581	\label{definition-purely-inseparable}
1582	Let $F$ be a field of characteristic $p > 0$. Let $K/F$ be an extension.
1583	\begin{enumerate}
1584	\item An element $\alpha \in K$ is {\it purely inseparable} over $F$
1585	if there exists a power $q$ of $p$ such that $\alpha^q \in F$.
1586	\item The extension $K/F$ is said to be {\it purely inseparable}
1587	if and only if every element of $K$ is purely inseparable over $F$.
1588	\end{enumerate}
1589	If we have a field extension $L/M$ (with no condition on the characteristic
1590	of $M$), then we will say the extension is {\it purely inseparable}
1591	if either $L = M$ or the characteristic of $M$ is a prime number $p$
1592	and $L/M$ is purely inseparable in the sense defined above.
1593	\end{definition}
1594	
1595	\noindent
1596	Observe that a purely inseparable extension is necessarily algebraic.
1597	Let $F$ be a field of characteristic $p > 0$.

