\textbf{Live route (the iter-150+ Lean body): the HYBRID route (C), itemised as (BR.5$'$) below.} The Lean declaration \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.mem\_range\_algebraMap\_of\_D\_eq\_zero} carries \texttt{[CharZero k]} in its signature and proves the forward direction ``$D b = 0 \Rightarrow b \in \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$'' by an \mbox{MvPolynomial}-side joint-kernel collapse $+$ \texttt{SubmersivePresentation} lift $+$ \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.map\_D} functoriality reduction (route (C)); its sub-steps (C.a)--(C.c) are closed in tree and the single residual \texttt{sorry} is exactly the (C.d) transfer step. The two earlier itemisations --- the characteristic-$0$ \texttt{Differential.ContainConstants}-via-instance route (p2)/(BR.1)--(BR.5), and the characteristic-$p$ Cartier-direction route (p1) --- are \textbf{SUPERSEDED alternatives}: they are retained below as an auditable record of the routes the iter-145--149 lanes explored, but the iter-150 Lane~2 prover lane PIVOTED off both (the live body registers \emph{no} \texttt{Differential B} typeclass instance and runs \emph{no} Frobenius iteration). The base inclusion ``$b \in \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B) \Rightarrow D b = 0$'' is the standard \texttt{Derivation.map\_algebraMap} (Mathlib, \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Derivation.Basic}) and supplies the reverse direction independently of the route chosen.

\emph{Live route (C) --- HYBRID joint-kernel transfer (BR.5$'$).} This is the route the iter-150+ Lean body commits to. It closes the forward direction in characteristic $0$ by transferring the kernel question from $B$ to its free polynomial presentation $P.\mathrm{Ring} = \mathrm{MvPolynomial}\,\iota\,k$, where the kernel-equals-constants fact is elementary, then pushing the conclusion back along the standard-smooth presentation map $\pi \colon P.\mathrm{Ring} \to B$. The four sub-steps, parallel in style to (BR.1)--(BR.5) and (p1.a)--(p1.f):
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(C.a)] \emph{FREE-CASE.} Over $k$ of characteristic $0$, if the universal K\"ahler derivation $D$ kills $f \in \mathrm{MvPolynomial}\,\sigma\,k$ (i.e.\ $D f = 0$), then $f \in (\mathrm{MvPolynomial.C}).\mathrm{range}$ ($f$ is a constant). Proof: $D f = 0$ forces every partial $\mathrm{pderiv}_i f = 0$ (via the explicit free basis \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.mvPolynomialBasis}, with $\mathrm{repr}(D f)\,i = \mathrm{pderiv}_i f$); the coefficient identity $\mathrm{coeff}_{u - \mathrm{single}_i 1}(\mathrm{pderiv}_i f) = \mathrm{coeff}_u f \cdot (u\,i)$ for $u\,i \geq 1$ then forces every non-constant coefficient to vanish in characteristic $0$ (where the integer $u\,i$ is invertible). \textbf{Closed in Lean}: project lemmas \texttt{\_mvPoly\_coeff\_pderiv\_at\_shifted}, \texttt{\_mvPoly\_mem\_range\_C\_of\_pderiv\_eq\_zero}, \texttt{\_mvPoly\_mem\_range\_C\_of\_D\_eq\_zero} (\texttt{AlgebraicJacobian/Cotangent/ChartAlgebra.lean}; \texttt{private}, not in Mathlib).
  \item[(C.b)] \emph{Standard-smooth presentation.} Extract a \texttt{SubmersivePresentation}\,$P$ from the \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension}\,$n$\,$k$\,$B$ hypothesis (via \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmooth.out}), giving a polynomial ring $P.\mathrm{Ring} = \mathrm{MvPolynomial}\,\iota\,k$ together with a surjective $k$-algebra map $\pi = \mathtt{algebraMap}\,P.\mathrm{Ring}\,B$ (surjectivity by \texttt{Algebra.Generators.algebraMap\_surjective}). \textbf{Closed in Lean.}
  \item[(C.c)] \emph{Lift $+$ functoriality.} Lift $b \in B$ to $\tilde b \in P.\mathrm{Ring}$ along the surjection $\pi$; the functoriality identity \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.map\_D} turns the hypothesis $D_B b = 0$ into $(\mathtt{map}\,k\,k\,P.\mathrm{Ring}\,B)(D_A \tilde b) = 0$, i.e.\ $D_A \tilde b \in \ker(\mathtt{map}\,k\,k\,P.\mathrm{Ring}\,B)$. \textbf{Closed in Lean} (the \texttt{\_hFunct} step).
  \item[(C.d)] \emph{Transfer step --- the residual \texttt{sorry}.} Modify $\tilde b$ to some $\alpha \in P.\mathrm{Ring}$ with $\pi(\alpha) = b$ (same image under the presentation map) AND $D_A \alpha = 0$ in $\Omega_{P.\mathrm{Ring}/k}$; then (C.a) applied to $\alpha$ gives $\alpha \in (\mathrm{MvPolynomial.C}).\mathrm{range}$, and the scalar-tower factorisation $\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B = \pi \circ (\mathrm{MvPolynomial.C})$ yields $b \in \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$. The obstruction to producing $\alpha$ is the description of the kernel: by \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.ker\_map\_of\_surjective}, $\ker(\mathtt{map}\,k\,k\,P.\mathrm{Ring}\,B)$ is the $P.\mathrm{Ring}$-submodule generated by $\{D r : r \in I\}$ (where $I = \ker \pi$) together with the $I \cdot \Omega_{P.\mathrm{Ring}/k}$ part. Subtracting a Leibniz combination $\sum_j a_j r_j$ ($r_j \in I$) absorbs the $D(I)$ part, leaving $D_A \alpha_1 \in I \cdot \Omega_{P.\mathrm{Ring}/k}$, and freeness of $\Omega_{P.\mathrm{Ring}/k}$ on $\{\mathrm dx_i\}$ reads this as ``each $\mathrm{pderiv}_i \alpha_1 \in I$''. Two closure paths: \textbf{(S5.a)} explicit \texttt{ker\_map\_of\_surjective} unfolding $+$ \texttt{Finsupp.linearCombination} unpacking $+$ Leibniz iteration ($\sim 30$ LOC); \textbf{(S5.b)} abstract bypass via \texttt{Algebra.FormallySmooth.subsingleton\_h1Cotangent} (the $H^1$ cotangent-complex vanishing for formally smooth $B$) deriving $\ker D_B \subseteq \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$ directly ($\sim 10$--$20$ LOC). \textbf{This is the single residual \texttt{sorry}} in the KDM Lean body; it is the iter-151+ prover target.
\end{itemize}
Plainly: sub-steps (C.a)--(C.c) are closed in the Lean tree (the iter-150 deposit lands $\sim 190$ LOC of helper machinery --- the four \texttt{\_mvPoly\_*} \texttt{private} lemmas supporting (C.a) plus the \texttt{\_hFunct} functoriality reduction of (C.c)), and the residual \texttt{sorry} is exactly the (C.d) transfer step. A prover directed at ``the transfer step'' should target (C.d) via either (S5.a) or (S5.b), \emph{not} the (BR.5) \texttt{Differential.ContainConstants} instance of the superseded (p2) route below.

